Kea is the new Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) server in Red Hat Enterprise Linux 10, replacing ISC DHCP. You can set up Kea to provide DHCPv4, DHCPv6, or both services.

Here's how to set up a Kea DHCP server:

**1. Install Kea**

Install the Kea package:
```bash
dnf install kea
```

**2. Configure Kea DHCPv4**

Kea uses separate configuration files and systemd services for DHCPv4 and DHCPv6.
The DHCPv4 configuration file is located at `/etc/kea/kea-dhcp4.conf`.

Here is an example configuration for DHCPv4, assuming a network interface `enp7s0`, network ID `192.168.10.0/24`, DHCP server IP `192.168.10.1`, subnet range `192.168.10.100 - 192.168.10.200`, gateway `192.168.10.1`, and DNS server `192.168.10.1`:

```json
{
  "Dhcp4": {
    "interfaces-config": {
      "interfaces": [ "enp7s0" ]
    },
    "subnet4": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "subnet": "192.168.10.0/24",
        "pools": [
          {
            "pool": "192.168.10.100 - 192.168.10.200"
          }
        ],
        "option-data": [
          {
            "space": "dhcp4",
            "name": "routers",
            "code": 3,
            "data": "192.168.10.1"
          },
          {
            "space": "dhcp4",
            "name": "domain-name-servers",
            "code": 6,
            "data": "192.168.10.1"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "loggers": [
      {
        "name": "kea-dhcp4",
        "output_options": [
          {
            "output": "stdout"
          }
        ],
        "severity": "INFO"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

**3. Verify DHCPv4 Configuration**

Check the syntax of your `kea-dhcp4.conf` file:
```bash
kea-dhcp4 -t /etc/kea/kea-dhcp4.conf
```
If there are syntax errors, fix them before proceeding.

**4. Configure Firewall for DHCPv4**

Allow incoming DHCPv4 traffic through the firewall:
```bash
firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=dhcp
firewall-cmd --reload
```

**5. Enable and Start Kea DHCPv4 Service**

Enable and start the `kea-dhcp4` systemd service:
```bash
systemctl enable --now kea-dhcp4
```

**6. Configure Kea DHCPv6 (Optional)**

If you are configuring an IPv6 network, edit the `/etc/kea/kea-dhcp6.conf` file. An example configuration would be:

```json
{
  "Dhcp6": {
    "interfaces-config": {
      "interfaces": [ "enp7s0" ]
    },
    "subnet6": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "subnet": "2001:db8:1::/64",
        "pools": [
          {
            "pool": "2001:db8:1::1000 - 2001:db8:1::2000"
          }
        ],
        "option-data": [
          {
            "space": "dhcp6",
            "name": "dns-servers",
            "code": 23,
            "data": "2001:db8:1::1"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "loggers": [
      {
        "name": "kea-dhcp6",
        "output_options": [
          {
            "output": "stdout"
          }
        ],
        "severity": "INFO"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

**7. Verify DHCPv6 Configuration**

Check the syntax of your `kea-dhcp6.conf` file:
```bash
kea-dhcp6 -t /etc/kea/kea-dhcp6.conf
```
Fix any syntax errors.

**8. Configure Firewall for DHCPv6**

Allow incoming DHCPv6 traffic through the firewall:
```bash
firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=dhcpv6
firewall-cmd --reload
```

**9. Enable and Start Kea DHCPv6 Service**

Enable and start the `kea-dhcp6` systemd service:
```bash
systemctl enable --now kea-dhcp6
```

**10. Verification**

On a client machine configured to use DHCP, check if it received an IP address from your Kea server:
```bash
ip address show <interface>
```
Replace `<interface>` with the actual network interface name on your client.

You can also check which IPv4 and IPv6 addresses Kea is listening on:
```bash
ss -lunp | grep -E 'kea-dhcp(4|6)'
```

Sources:
- [Managing networking infrastructure services](https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/10/html-single/managing_networking_infrastructure_services/index)
- [How to configure/setup a PXE server on RHEL 10 ?](https://access.redhat.com/solutions/7126352)

